</solution>
</exercise>
</note>
<note id="fs-id1167834219382" class="try">
<exercise id="fs-id1167835301574">
<problem id="fs-id1167834222478">
<para id="fs-id1167831921158">The manufacturer of a weight training bench spends $120 to build each bench and sells them for $170. The manufacturer also has fixed costs each month of $150,000.</para>
<para id="fs-id1167835320313"><span class="token">ⓐ</span> Find the cost function <emphasis effect="italics">C</emphasis> when <emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> benches are manufactured.</para>
<para id="fs-id1167834063564"><span class="token">ⓑ</span> Find the revenue function <emphasis effect="italics">R</emphasis> when <emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> benches are sold.</para>
<para id="fs-id1167835371350"><span class="token">ⓒ</span> Show the break-even point by graphing both the Revenue and Cost functions on the same grid.</para>
<para id="fs-id1167835348638"><span class="token">ⓓ</span> Find the break-even point. Interpret what the break-even point means.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1167835209283">
<para id="fs-id1167831923586"><span class="token">ⓐ</span> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>120</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>150,000</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math></para>
<para id="fs-id1167835338652"><span class="token">ⓑ</span> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>R</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>170</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></para>
<para id="fs-id1167834191196"><span class="token">ⓒ</span><newline/>
<media id="fs-id1167835596157" alt="Figure shows a graph with two intersecting lines. One of them passes through the origin.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/CNX_IntAlg_Figure_04_03_203_img_new.jpg"/>
</media>
</para>
<para id="fs-id1167834309568"><span class="token">ⓓ</span> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>3,000</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math>; when 3,000 benches are sold, the revenue and costs are both $510,000</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</note>
